---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Method, political stylometry">
  <article class="container">
    <header class="article-hero">
      <p class="byline">Method · updated 2026-06-14</p>
      <h1>Method</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Everything below is reproducible from public data at
        data.riksdagen.se plus the eight 2022 party manifestos. Source
        code is on
        <a href="https://github.com/freol35241/ps-sverige">GitHub</a>.
      </p>
    </header>

    <h2>Data sources</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>2,501 chamber votes</strong> from parliamentary years
      2022/23 to 2025/26, fetched as bulk dumps from
      <code>data.riksdagen.se/dataset/votering/</code>. 872,849 individual
      roll-call entries from 424 members.</li>
      <li><strong>54,914 chamber speeches</strong> from the same period
      (replies, interpellation answers and main speeches) fetched as
      bulk dumps from
      <code>data.riksdagen.se/dataset/anforande/</code>.</li>
      <li><strong>10,931 dissenting opinions (reservationer)</strong>
      extracted from 858 committee reports, fetched via
      <code>data.riksdagen.se/utskottsforslag/</code> and
      <code>data.riksdagen.se/dokumentstatus/</code>. 2.8 million words
      of text in total.</li>
      <li><strong>3,211 majority-opinion sections</strong> ("Utskottets
      ställningstagande") from the same reports. The majority's
      equivalent of a reservation.</li>
      <li><strong>3,696 manifesto sentences</strong> across the eight
      2022 party manifestos from the SND "Vi vill" archive (public
      domain). Manifesto length varies from 1.6k words (KD) to 21k
      words (SD).</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The behavioural map</h2>
    <p>
      A 349-by-2,501 member-by-vote matrix is built from the chamber
      record (Yes = +1, No = -1, Abstain or Absent = 0). PCA on this
      matrix yields the two-dimensional projection shown in the main
      article. PC1 (46 % of variance) separates the Tidö bloc from the
      opposition. PC2 (13.5 %) splits the opposition into an S arm and
      a V/MP/C arm.
    </p>
    <p>
      To track movement over the mandate, the same projection is run
      per parliamentary year. The bloc collapse and Tidö agreement
      trend (figures 07 and 08) come from year-by-year PCAs aligned
      through Procrustes rotation so the axes are comparable across
      time.
    </p>

    <h2>Topic clustering</h2>
    <p>
      All 2,480 contested decision points are embedded with a Swedish
      language model
      (<a href="https://huggingface.co/KBLab/sentence-bert-swedish-cased">KBLab/sentence-bert-swedish-cased</a>,
      a 768-dim model trained on Swedish text by the National Library's
      KB Lab). We use each committee report's title plus the point's
      heading as input, not the proposal text itself, which is
      dominated by procedural formulae.
    </p>
    <p>
      KMeans clustering into 28 groups yields a topic structure that
      tracks committee jurisdictions reasonably well. Migration,
      climate, schools and health care are among the cleanest. Manual
      inspection of top terms per cluster confirms the grouping is
      meaningful. The same 28 topics are used downstream for reasoning
      vectors and for stated-vs-revealed matching.
    </p>

    <h2>Manifesto element classification</h2>
    <p>
      Each manifesto is split into sentences with abbreviation handling.
      Each sentence is scored against three curated regex pools:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Diagnosis</strong>: language describing the current
      problematic state. Negative-framed observations and present-state
      critique.</li>
      <li><strong>End state</strong>: aspirational future-state
      statements ("vi vill se", "Sverige ska vara", "ett land där").</li>
      <li><strong>Mechanism</strong>: concrete policy proposals using
      action verbs in future or proposal tense ("höja", "skärpa",
      "reformera", "införa").</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      A sentence gets the element with the highest score, or "other"
      if no pool matched. In ties, end-state takes precedence as the
      rarest and most diagnostic of the three. A separate value
      vocabulary of 20 terms is matched in parallel, with per-party
      frequencies normalised per 1000 words and z-scored across the
      eight parties.
    </p>
    <p>
      The classifier is keyword-based by design: fast, transparent,
      easy to audit. The regex pools are open in the code and can be
      revised. Differences in classifier sensitivity affect absolute
      shares but not the cross-party comparisons that drive the main
      findings.
    </p>

    <h2>Reasoning vectors</h2>
    <p>
      Reservation texts are segmented to their "Ställningstagande"
      sections, where the substantive argument lives. Per (party,
      topic) we take up to 20 of the longest reservations; each text
      is embedded into a 768-dim vector and the mean is stored.
    </p>
    <p>
      For the governing parties (M, KD, L), almost no reservations
      exist because they are the majority. We instead use the
      "Utskottets ställningstagande" sections from the committee
      reports, where the majority explains its choice. The text is
      lightly recast from third person to first person so it reads in
      the same voice as opposition reservations.
    </p>

    <h2>Stated vs revealed (topic-matched)</h2>
    <p>
      The most direct manifesto-vs-parliament comparison would be
      cosine similarity between each party's mean manifesto vector
      and its mean reservation vector. This is misleading because it
      conflates topical content with register. Cabinet parties write
      polished committee formulations on different topics than the
      opposition writes detailed reservations about.
    </p>
    <p>
      We instead compute the comparison within (party, topic) cells.
      Each manifesto sentence is assigned to its nearest of the 28
      topic centroids by SBERT cosine, with a minimum similarity
      threshold of 0.30 to drop off-topic sentences. Cells with fewer
      than five on-topic manifesto sentences are dropped. The
      remaining 75 cells across eight parties form the matrix of
      figure 27.
    </p>

    <h2>Coalition and behavioural signals</h2>
    <p>
      Beyond the vote-matrix PCA, two additional behavioural signals
      surface in the article:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Reservation co-signing.</strong> When two parties
      put their names on the same reservation they share a concrete
      alternative proposal. Co-signing counts are direct structural
      evidence of mechanism alignment. SD has zero co-signed
      reservations with any cabinet party across the entire mandate.</li>
      <li><strong>Tidö collapse and SD reservation drop.</strong> The
      mean pairwise centroid distance between the four Tidö parties,
      and the count of reservations filed per party per year, are
      computed directly from the chamber record without further
      modelling.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Limitations</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Topic clustering follows committee jurisdiction</strong>,
        not voter mental categories.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Reasoning vectors include ministers reading
        government-drafted statements.</strong> Not always the
        individual member's own voice. For the cabinet, this is a
        structural inevitability.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>The element classifier is keyword-based.</strong> A
        sentence that argues end-state ideas in mechanism language
        will be misclassified. The regex pools are open in the code
        for revision.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>KD and MP have thin manifestos.</strong> KD's 1.6k-word
        manifesto yields only one topic with sufficient on-topic
        material; MP yields three. Their stated-vs-revealed bars are
        shown but should not be over-interpreted.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Decisions taken outside the chamber are not in the
        data.</strong> Government decisions, agency decisions, EU
        votes and delegated decisions are invisible to a chamber-vote
        based analysis.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Questions not yet voted on are absent entirely.</strong>
        Only what has been processed since September 2022.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Reproducibility</h2>
    <p>
      All data fetching, processing, analysis and site generation is
      written in Python and openly available on
      <a href="https://github.com/freol35241/ps-sverige">GitHub</a>.
      Raw data is loaded directly from
      <code>data.riksdagen.se</code> and the SND archive; we do not
      redistribute it. The analysis can be re-run from scratch on an
      ordinary machine in about an hour, including text embedding.
      Results in this article are based on data available through
      June 2026.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
